# shared/security/.env.vault.example
# Encrypted Environment Variables Template using dotenv-vault

# This file is an example of how to structure your encrypted environment variables.
# Use dotenv-vault to encrypt and manage your environment variables securely.

# Steps to use dotenv-vault:
# 1. Install dotenv-vault: npm install -g dotenv-vault
# 2. Initialize dotenv-vault: dotenv-vault new
# 3. Login to dotenv-vault: dotenv-vault login
# 4. Push your environment variables: dotenv-vault push
# 5. Encrypt your environment variables: dotenv-vault build
# 6. Share the .env.vault file with your team (commit to git)
# 7. Use the DOTENV_KEY in your deployment environment

# Example .env.vault structure (encrypted):
# DOTENV_VAULT=
#   dotenv://:key_1234@dotenv.org/vault/.env.vault?environment=production

# Example DOTENV_KEY for deployment:
# DOTENV_KEY="dotenv://:key_1234@dotenv.org/vault/.env.vault?environment=production"

# Example decrypted environment variables (for reference only):
# JWT_SECRET="your-strong-jwt-secret-key-here"
# ALLOWED_ORIGINS="https://yourdomain.com,https://www.yourdomain.com"
# OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-your-openai-api-key"
# SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY="your-supabase-service-key"
# LIVEKIT_API_KEY="your-livekit-api-key"
# LIVEKIT_API_SECRET="your-livekit-api-secret"
# GOOGLE_API_KEY="your-google-api-key"
# RATE_LIMIT_POINTS="10"
# RATE_LIMIT_DURATION="60"